Let us examine the data

class_names <- c('airplane', 'automobile', 'bird', 'cat', 'deer',
               'dog', 'frog', 'horse', 'ship', 'truck')

index <- 1:30
par(mfcol = c(5,6), mar = rep(1, 4), oma = rep(0.2, 4))
cifar$train$x[index,,,] %>% 
  purrr::array_tree(1) %>%
  purrr::set_names(class_names[cifar$train$y[index] + 1]) %>% 
  purrr::map(as.raster, max = 255) %>%
  purrr::iwalk(~{plot(.x); title(.y)})

Create the convolutional part of the network:

  1. Convolutional layer with 32 filters of size 3x3 and ReLU activation
  2. Max pooling layer with a pool size of 2x2
  3. Convolutional layer with 64 filters of size 3x3 and ReLU activation
  4. Max pooling layer with a pool size of 2x2
  5. layer_conv_2d(filters = 64, kernel_size = c(3,3), activation = relu)

Notice the input size. Each image is a 32x32 image, and we have 3 channels for color (R,G,B)

model <- keras_model_sequential() %>% 
  layer_conv_2d(filters = 32, kernel_size = c(3,3), activation = "relu", 
                input_shape = c(32,32,3)) %>% 
  layer_max_pooling_2d(pool_size = c(2,2)) %>% 
  layer_conv_2d(filters = 64, kernel_size = c(3,3), activation = "relu") %>% 
  layer_max_pooling_2d(pool_size = c(2,2)) %>% 
  layer_conv_2d(filters = 64, kernel_size = c(3,3), activation = "relu")

summary(model)

Add the Fully Connected layers that will make the classification

model %>% 
  layer_flatten() %>% 
  layer_dense(units = 64, activation = "relu") %>% 
  layer_dense(units = 10, activation = "softmax")

Compile and train

model %>% compile(
  optimizer = "adam",
  loss = "sparse_categorical_crossentropy",
  metrics = "accuracy"
)

history <- model %>% 
  fit(
    x = cifar$train$x, y = cifar$train$y,
    epochs = 10,
    validation_data = unname(cifar$test),
    verbose = 2
  )

Plot training curves

plot(history)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Evaluate Model

evaluate(model, cifar$test$x, cifar$test$y, verbose = 0)
##     loss accuracy 
## 1.094812 0.647800

Using the model to make predictions

# Get probabilities for each class per sample
probs <- model %>% predict(cifar$test$x)
# Pick the class with the highest probability from the first sample
class <- which.max(probs[1, ])
# Use class names to identify the article
print(class_names[class])
## [1] "dog"

Let us visualize a few predictions

Note that the true label is the one between brackets

par(mfcol = c(5,6), mar = rep(1, 4), oma = rep(0.2, 4))
cifar$test$x[index,,,] %>% 
  purrr::array_tree(1) %>%

  purrr::map(as.raster, max = 255) %>%

Early stopping

model <- keras_model_sequential() %>% 
  layer_conv_2d(filters = 32, kernel_size = c(3,3), activation = "relu", 
                input_shape = c(32,32,3)) %>% 
  layer_max_pooling_2d(pool_size = c(2,2)) %>% 
  layer_conv_2d(filters = 64, kernel_size = c(3,3), activation = "relu") %>% 
  layer_max_pooling_2d(pool_size = c(2,2)) %>% 
  layer_conv_2d(filters = 64, kernel_size = c(3,3), activation = "relu") %>% 
  layer_flatten() %>% 
  layer_dense(units = 64, activation = "relu") %>% 
  layer_dense(units = 10, activation = "softmax")

model %>% compile(
  optimizer = "adam",
  loss = "sparse_categorical_crossentropy",
  metrics = "accuracy"
)

history <- model %>% 
  fit(
    x = cifar$train$x, y = cifar$train$y,
    epochs = 10,
    validation_data = unname(cifar$test),
    verbose = 2,
    callbacks = list(
      callback_early_stopping(
        monitor = "val_loss",
        min_delta = 0.05,
        patience = 3,
        restore_best_weights = TRUE
      )
    )
  )

plot(history)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

evaluate(model, cifar$test$x, cifar$test$y, verbose = 0)
##     loss accuracy 
## 1.018292 0.658200
